nodes.title: Sampler group toggle
widgets_values: If both sampler groups are toggled on, then sampler group 1 will be used.
Use the Sampler Scheduler Settings (JPS) node above to pick the sampler.

nodes.title: If your images are too sharp
widgets_values:
Find and bypass all the Image Filter Adjustment nodes or:

1. Unpin them
2. Expand them
3. Adjust the settings

...or delete them.

nodes.title: Concat Conditioning
widgets_values:
From the ComfyUI wiki:

Imagine that you are cooking a dish, "conditioning_to" is the basic recipe, and "conditioning_from" are some additional seasonings or condiments. The ConditioningConcat class is like a tool that helps you add these seasonings to the recipe, making your dish more colorful and rich.

nodes.title: Note: USDU Stuff
widgets_values:
For 2x Upscale:
If not using seams_fix_mode HALF TILE:

I recommend using 256 to 512 for tile_padding. This setting affects what USDU is "looking" at when generating the tiled image. The higher the number, the more accurate it should be. The drawback to increasing this is longer generation time.

If using seams_fix_mode HALF TILE:

I recommend 192 tile_padding. 128 is probably the lowest I would go. HALF TILE is supposed to help with the quality of the output and is effectively adding tiles between the normal tiles.

Ghosting and other garbage:

If you are getting a ton of ghosting in USDU, try lowering/increasing the steps/denoise and/or increasing the tile_padding setting. 

My denoise settings are pretty aggressive (IMO) with the denoise being at (0.35 without ControlNet and even higher with ControlNet) and the low tile_padding size. Also you an try describing less in your prompt.

The original project page recommends 0.1 to 0.2 denoise for upscaling and up to 0.35 for enhancing the image.

The recommended tile size for SDXL models is 512 (based on Google search). Depending on how big you are going, you may have to go even bigger with the tile padding. In those cases, you probably need to bump up the mask blur value if seams start appearing. 

Upscale models, sampler, and schedulers can also influence this as well. There's too many factors to pin it down to one setting.

Changing the Detail Daemon settings or toggling off Detail Daemon can also help.

nodes.title: Note: Dynamic Thresholding & FreeU_V2
widgets_values:
The CFG node near the KSampler should be set to whatever high value you want. Not more than double the normal setting with how I have it set up.

If you want to go higher, you'll need to disconnect the input noodles from the Dynamic Thresholding node for everything other than the model. Then you can set the values to whatever you like manually and go crazy with the CFG setting.

Set the minimum CFG to your preferred number. I try to keep it close to the low end of whatever sampler I am using.

threshold_percentile adjusts how quickly the the image is clamped. 1.00 means it will be super aggressive. Usually, you want to be somewhere from 0.90 to 0.99.

interpolate_phi controls the image saturation and how the CFG scale is applied over time during the generation process. It essentially acts as a factor that interpolates the effects of high and low CFG scales. A value of 0 for Interpolate Phi disables dynamic thresholding and uses the main CFG scale. Values between 0.7 and 0.9 often produce the best results. (per Google)

The project page recommends using Half Cosine Up for the mode selections, but it never hurts to experiment.

Otherwise, you can just bypass these nodes and use CFG like normal.

FreeU V2: It works well with some models while completely wrecking the output of others. I recommend not using FreeU V2 unless you are someone who loves having extra settings to play with. You can bypass/un-bypass it or just delete it and the noodles will connect into the Dynamic Thresholding node. The settings I have on there are based on someone else's testing with SDXL.

nodes.title: Note: Detail Daemon
widgets_values:
Video explanation on how to use Detail Daemon by Nerdy Rodent:

https://youtu.be/dG9HfgngsqM?si=hqvUalq0uliWctY6

Project page:

https://github.com/Jonseed/ComfyUI-Detail-Daemon

TL;DR

Keep the factor setting at 0.95 to 0.99

Start and end settings are percentile with 1.0 being 100% just like the ControlNet setting.

nodes.title: Note: ControlNet
widgets_values: I only use TTPlanet_TileSimple, but if you're using ControlNet, I assume you know what you're doing.

nodes.title: Watermark Detection
widgets_values:
If you see a white mask in the Watermark Mask node, then something was detected. 

Detection Threshold: Raise or lower the detection threshold as needed. (Yes, even down to 0.00001). Lowering it makes it more sensitive. 1 is the highest and basically makes it detect nothing.

Disclaimer: this does not always detect watermarks, but it does work most of the time. Some generated watermarks, text, etc., just fail to get detected no matter what.

This is a CLIPSeg method of doing this using way less nodes, but I have run into issues with that method and will stick with what works for me.

BBOX Detector (SEGS): 

You can adjust the prompts in this node to whatever you want. I think the default is "all".

nodes.title: Detailer Helper Prompts
widgets_values:
These are just the "wildcard spec" entries on the FaceDetailer nodes.

Describing what is being detailed can help the results if you feel the detailer isn't quite getting it.

Leaving these text boxes blank will cause no issues otherwise.

If you want to actually make use of wildcards, then you will likely need to disconnect these text boxes from the FaceDetailer nodes.
